The paper deals with security games, which are a subfield of game theory (cs.GT). It specifically focuses on the spatio-temporal aspect of these games, which involves movement on a real line, making it relevant to the sub-category of computational geometry and topology (cs.CR). The paper also proposes an algorithm for computing the Nash equilibrium, which involves optimization and decision-making, making it relevant to the sub-category of artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The algorithm itself involves polynomial-time computation, which is a topic in the sub-category of data structures and algorithms (cs.DS). Finally, the paper deals with the practical issue of protecting infrastructure, which is a topic in the sub-category of social and information networks (cs.SI).
